From: aorus-5090-egpu <noreply@example.invalid>
Date: 2026-05-08
Subject: [PATCH] AORUS Patch 0029 — close-path DIAG instrumentation + AER err_handlers surface completion

Extends our open-side DIAG infrastructure (probe-end / startdev-entry
/ pre-rmInit / post-rmInit-{OK,FAIL}) into the close path so we can
diagnose the close-path-bug class (architecture.md Problem 2 +
Problem 4) by capturing state diff across the open->work->close->
reopen lifecycle.

Three components:

PART A — close-path DIAG sites (4 new sites in nv.c):

  - close-entry      — at top of nvidia_close_callback after nvl
                       check; captures pre-close state. Full DIAG
                       only on last-close (usage_count==1).
  - pre-stop         — just before nv_close_device under ldata_lock.
                       Captures state right before teardown can fire.
  - post-shutdown    — inside nv_stop_device after rm_disable_adapter
                       or nv_shutdown_adapter. Always last-close
                       (nv_stop_device is only entered when
                       usage_count reaches 0). Most diagnostic site.
  - close-exit       — at end of nvidia_close_callback. Captures
                       fully-torn-down post-close state.

  Each site emits a one-line marker logging usage_count. On the
  last-close path, additionally calls tb_egpu_lever_m_diag_dump and
  tb_egpu_dump_aer_trigger_event for full state + AER snapshot. The
  diff between these and the open-side DIAG entries identifies what
  the close path mutates in PMC_BOOT_0 / WPR2 / LnkSta / AER state
  that breaks the next open.

  Helper tb_egpu_lever_m_close_path_diag() lives in nv-lever-m-recover.c.

PART B — pci_error_handlers surface completion (nv-pci.c):

  - mmio_enabled callback: kernel may dispatch this between
    error_detected returning CAN_RECOVER and slot_reset. We always
    return NEED_RESET so this normally won't fire, but kernel
    internals occasionally invoke it via pci_walk_bus during AER
    recovery. Wired up for completeness, observability, and
    future-proofing. Body: dump DIAG + AER snapshot, return
    PCI_ERS_RESULT_RECOVERED.

  - cor_error_detected callback: proactive observability for
    correctable AER errors that don't reach the uncorrectable
    path. The Gen3 demotion observed 2026-05-07 (Br_AER_Cor=0x1 +
    GPU_AER_UncMsk=0x400000 demoting Internal Error to Cor=0x2000)
    is exactly this class. No state change; pure observability.

  Both wired into nv_pci_err_handlers struct.

PART C — version.mk bump to aorus.11 to mark this build distinctly
  from the aorus.10 production build (patches 0024-0028).

Risk per feedback_observability_perturbs_bug: bpftrace, ioctl-trace,
CUDA_LAUNCH_BLOCKING all materially perturbed the failure mode in
past investigations. Our DIAG dump uses ioremap+ioread32+iounmap
(passive MMIO) and tb_egpu_dump_aer_trigger_event uses PCI
config-space reads only (passive). Both helpers have been live
since 2026-05-06 in 4 open-side DIAG sites without observable
perturbation. The new 4 close-path sites follow the same pattern;
if behaviour changes after this patch, baseline-vs-instrumented
comparison will isolate it.

Refs: docs/architecture.md Problem 2 + Problem 4;
      memory/feedback_avoid_nvidia_smi_for_state_checks.md;
      memory/feedback_observability_perturbs_bug.md.
---
--- a/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.h
+++ b/kernel-open/nvidia/nv-lever-m-recover.h
@@ -158,6 +158,36 @@
